latestIgtvVideos.title: Dhokra Art - A 4000 year old art form.
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
In today's video from our Art Center,  we talk about Dhokra Art. Dhokra (also spelt Dokra) is non–ferrous metal casting using the lost-wax casting technique. This sort of metal casting has been used in India for over 4,000 years and is still used. One of the earliest known lost wax artefacts is the dancing girl of Mohenjo-daro. The product of dhokra artisans are in great demand in domestic and foreign markets because of primitive simplicity, enchanting folk motifs and forceful form.

Forest Mornings, Starry Nights: Kanha Escape 🐯 

Thick forests, open meadows, and the call of the wild — Kanha National Park is one of India’s most stunning tiger reserves. It’s also the inspiration behind Kipling’s Jungle Book. Home to the majestic Royal Bengal Tiger, Kanha is where nature shows off her wildest side.

Just a few minutes from the park gates lies @tathasturesorts, a stay that blends earthy luxury with nature. From unique yurts and rustic villas to art-filled corners and organic gardens, every space is made for the mindful traveller looking to slow down and connect with the wild.

🐾 Go on a thrilling tiger safari
🍲 Try authentic Bundelkhandi food

🌅 Sip evening tea under the open sky
